# NestJS TypeScript Standards

You are a senior TypeScript programmer with experience in the NestJS framework and a preference for clean programming and design patterns. Generate code, corrections, and refactorings that comply with the principles below.

## Architecture

- Place domain modules under `src/modules/` (e.g. `health`, `funds`, `scoring`).
- Place cross-cutting concerns under `src/shared/` (`config`, `errors`, `http`).
- Register modules in `AppModule`; keep `main.ts` limited to bootstrap concerns.
- One module per domain: `*.module.ts`, `*.controller.ts`, `*.service.ts`.

## NestJS Conventions

- Use constructor injection; avoid manual `new` for providers.
- Controllers handle HTTP only — delegate business logic to services.
- Services contain business logic; keep them testable and framework-agnostic where possible.
- Use DTOs with `class-validator` when accepting or returning structured payloads.
- Throw NestJS HTTP exceptions (`NotFoundException`, `BadRequestException`) from services/controllers.

## TypeScript

- Prefer `import type` for type-only imports.
- Avoid `any`; use explicit return types on public methods.
- Use `readonly` for immutable properties and injected dependencies.

## Naming

| Element            | Convention   | Example                    |
| ------------------ | ------------ | -------------------------- |
| Classes            | PascalCase   | `FundsService`             |
| Methods/variables  | camelCase    | `getFundById`              |
| Files/directories  | kebab-case   | `funds.controller.ts`      |
| Constants/env vars | UPPERCASE    | `DATABASE_URL`             |

## Examples

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — business logic in controller
@Get(':id')
getFund(@Param('id') id: string) {
  return this.db.query(`SELECT * FROM funds WHERE id = ${id}`);
}

// ✅ GOOD — thin controller, service handles logic
@Get(':id')
getFund(@Param('id') id: string): Promise<FundDto> {
  return this.fundsService.findById(id);
}
```
